recalls.Summary: BMW North America, LLC (BMW) is recalling certain model year 2016 BMW M2 Coupe vehicles, 2015-2017 M3 Sedan vehicles and 2015-2016 M4 Coupe and M4 Convertible vehicles.  During servicing of the rear differential for a prior service action, the rear sub-frame bolts may have been reused instead of being replaced.  Reuse of the existing bolts may cause the bolts to loosen.
recalls.Consequence: Loose rear sub-frame bolts may adversely affect vehicle handling and control, increasing the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: BMW will notify owners, and dealers will replace the rear sub-frame bolts with new bolts, free of charge.  The recall began on November 3, 2016.  Owners may contact BMW customer service at 1-800-525-7417.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: BMW of North America, LLC (BMW) is recalling certain model year 2015-2016 M3 Sedan vehicles manufactured May 30, 2015, to September 2, 2015, 2016 M4 Coupe vehicles manufactured July 3, 2015, to September 11, 2015, and 2015-2016 M4 Convertible vehicles manufactured May 29, 2015, to August 4, 2015. The affected vehicles have a driveshaft with a slip-joint that may not have been filled with grease.  As a result, the slip-joint may fail over time.
recalls.Consequence: If the slip-joint fails, there would be a loss of power to the rear axle and therefore the vehicle would stop moving, increasing the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: BMW will notify owners, and dealers will inspect the driveshaft, replacing it as necessary, free of charge.  The recall began on January 14, 2016.  Owners may contact BMW customer service at 1-800-525-7417.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: BMW of North America, LLC (BMW) is recalling certain 2014-2015 2 Series Coupe (228i, 228i xDrive, M235i), 3 Series Sedan (320i, 320i xDrive, 328i, 328i xDrive, 335i, 335i xDrive, M3, 328d, 328d xDrive), 4 Series Coupe (428i, 428i xDrive, 435i, 435i xDrive, M4), and 2015 4 Series Gran Coupe (428i, 428i xDrive, 435i, 435i xDrive) vehicles.  The head air bag inflator may fail at the weld joint, which can cause gas to leak from the inflator or result in an inflator rupture.
recalls.Consequence: An inflator that ruptures may cause sharp metal fragments to enter or exit the vehicle, increasing the risk of injury.  Additionally, an inflator that leaks gas may only partially inflate during a crash, increasing the risk of injury.
recalls.Remedy: Dealers will replace the head air bags, free of charge.  Owner notification letters were mailed November 4, 2024.  Owners may contact BMW customer service at 1-800-525-7417.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.nhtsa.gov.

The BMW OEM intercooler/charge air cooler is a known faulty equipment issue within this generation of cars/engine (S55 Engine, F80, F82, F87 chassis) and I have thousands of people within the community that were affected and willing to attest to this.   This issue is a safety risk as having the intercooler leak coolant into the combustion chambers this will be a catastrophically damage the engine.   As I've mentioned this problem has been confirmed by dealers and independent service centers, and I have thousands of people in the willing to attest to this being a very common issue in this generation of cars.   There is usually supposed to be a service warning/check engine light that comes up on the car when there is a coolant leak, I received nothing. The symptoms I've experienced are as the following: My radiator fans kept coming on after drives, I had to physically check that coolant was in fact leaking and the reservoir being bone dry within days, I scanned my vehicle for codes and of course the coolant leak code came back.

ON APRIL 10, 2020, I TOOK MY CAR INTO SERVICE AGAIN AS I WAS HAVING DRIVE TRAIN MALFUNCTIONS CONSTANTLY. SEVERAL WEEKS OF BEING IN THE SHOP, BMW SERVICE TECHNICIANS FOUND THAT COOLING FLUIDS HAD LEAKED FROM MY TOP MOUNTED INTERCOOLER, INTO THE INTAKE MANIFOLD AND THROUGH THE INTAKE VALVES, AND DIRECTLY INTO THE ENGINE OF MY VEHICLE.   SINCE THE ENGINE NOW NEEDED TO BE REPLACED, BMW OF FREMONT RECOMMENDED AND REQUESTED FOR AN ENGINE REPLACEMENT BUT BMW HAD REJECTED IT AND STATED THAT THEY FOUND SOME 'TUNE' IN THE VEHICLE. I PURCHASED AN EXTENDED WARRANTY AND MAINTENANCE PLAN FROM BMW DIRECTLY THAT IS STILL ACTIVE. MY ENGINE REPLACEMENT SHOULD BE COVERED UNDER WARRANTY BUT BMW IS NOT ADHERING TO THAT WARRANTY.   AFTER COUNTLESS CALLS AND EMAILS BEING SENT BACK AND FORTH BETWEEN ME AND BMW, NEW INFORMATION AROSE STATING THAT BMW FOUND THAT THE 'TUNE' FOUND IN MY VEHICLE WAS MERELY A VALVE CONTROLLER FOR MY EXHAUST SYSTEM. BMW OF FREMONT CLEARLY MENTIONED TO BMW THAT THIS LEAK IS NOT CAUSED BY OR EVEN REMOTELY CORRELATED TO THE VALVE CONTROLLER, AND THAT THIS ISSUE IS MECHANICAL, NOT SOFTWARE RELATED.  CLEARLY, THIS HAS NOTHING TO DO WITH THE MAJOR ISSUE AT HAND, WHICH IS THE LEAKING INTERCOOLER CAUSING MY ENGINE TO FAIL. IT IS A MAJOR SAFETY ISSUE FOR MY CAR TO BE RUN WITHOUT THE ENGINE REPLACEMENT, AS THE CAR NOW HAS A MUCH HIGHER CHANCE OF BEING HYDRO-LOCKED. MY CAR HAS NOW BEEN AT BMW OF FREMONT FOR THE PAST TWO MONTHS. I'M STILL PAYING MY MONTHLY DUES FOR THE VEHICLE DILIGENTLY EVEN THOUGH BMW HAS CAUSED THIS MANY ISSUES.   *TR

issues.title: Rod Bearing Failure
issues.description: The S55 engine in the F82 M4 is prone to rod bearing wear and failure, particularly in early production models. This can lead to catastrophic engine damage if not addressed.
issues.fix_description: Complete engine rebuild or replacement, rod bearing replacement with upgraded bearings
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes with high-quality oil, avoid aggressive driving until engine is warm, monitor oil analysis

issues.title: Charge Pipe Failure
issues.description: The plastic charge pipe connecting the intercooler to the throttle body is prone to cracking and bursting under boost pressure, causing loss of power.
issues.fix_description: Replace with upgraded aluminum or reinforced charge pipe
issues.prevention: Upgrade to aftermarket aluminum charge pipe, avoid aggressive tuning without supporting modifications

issues.title: Crank Hub/Harmonic Balancer Failure
issues.description: The crank hub can slip or fail on the S55 engine, causing timing issues and potential catastrophic engine damage.
issues.fix_description: Replace crank hub with upgraded version, potential engine rebuild if damage occurred
issues.prevention: Regular inspection of crank hub, avoid high RPM operation when engine is cold

issues.title: Carbon Fiber Driveshaft Failure
issues.description: The carbon fiber driveshaft can develop cracks or complete failure, particularly in high-mileage vehicles or those subjected to hard launches.
issues.fix_description: Replace driveshaft with OEM or upgraded steel alternative
issues.prevention: Avoid hard launches, inspect driveshaft regularly for cracks

issues.title: VANOS Solenoid Issues
issues.description: Variable valve timing solenoids can fail, causing poor engine performance and rough idle conditions.
issues.fix_description: Replace faulty VANOS solenoids and clean VANOS system
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, use high-quality oil, avoid extended oil change intervals

issues.title: Turbocharger Wastegate Rattle
issues.description: The turbocharger wastegates can develop rattling noises due to worn actuator arms or loose components.
symptoms: Noise when engine is turned off
issues.fix_description: Replace wastegate actuators or complete turbocharger replacement
issues.prevention: Allow engine to idle before shutdown, use quality fuel, regular maintenance

issues.title: Fuel Injector Failure
issues.description: High-pressure fuel injectors can fail due to carbon buildup and wear, causing misfires and rough running.
issues.fix_description: Replace faulty fuel injectors, perform walnut blasting to remove carbon buildup
issues.prevention: Use top-tier fuel, regular fuel system cleaning, avoid short trips

issues.title: Electronic Power Steering Failure
issues.description: The electric power steering system can fail, resulting in heavy steering or complete loss of power assistance.
issues.fix_description: Replace power steering control module or steering rack assembly
issues.prevention: Regular system diagnostics, avoid extreme steering inputs

issues.title: Adaptive LED Headlight Failure
issues.description: The adaptive LED headlight system can malfunction, causing uneven lighting patterns or complete headlight failure.
issues.fix_description: Replace headlight control modules or complete headlight assemblies
issues.prevention: Avoid aftermarket HID/LED conversions, regular electrical system checks

issues.title: DCT Transmission Clutch Wear
issues.description: The dual-clutch transmission can experience premature clutch wear, especially in vehicles used for frequent track driving or aggressive driving.
issues.fix_description: Replace clutch packs and transmission fluid, potential transmission rebuild
issues.prevention: Avoid aggressive launches, allow transmission to warm up, regular fluid changes

issues.title: Crankcase Ventilation System Failure
issues.description: The positive crankcase ventilation system can fail, leading to oil consumption issues and engine breathing problems.
issues.fix_description: Replace PCV valve and associated components, clean intake system
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, monitor oil consumption, use quality oil

editorial.tagline: Turbo torque meets M precision engineering
editorial.hero_blurb: The F82 M4 marked BMW's bold transition from naturally aspirated V8 to forced-induction inline-six power. This angular coupe delivers devastating straight-line performance while maintaining the M Division's commitment to driver engagement.
editorial.essence: The F82 M4 represents BMW's controversial yet successful pivot to turbocharged performance, trading the E92's screaming V8 for massive torque and improved efficiency. Despite purist protests, this generation proved that forced induction could deliver both crushing acceleration and genuine M car character.
editorial.heritage: Following the legendary E30 M3 and naturally aspirated E92 M3, the F82 M4 broke the naming convention while introducing BMW's S55 twin-turbo inline-six. This generation marked the split between M3 sedan and M4 coupe nomenclature, establishing the M4 as the dedicated two-door performance flagship.
editorial.design_philosophy: BMW's designers crafted an aggressive, angular aesthetic that emphasized the M4's turbocharged muscle. The prominent kidney grilles, flared fenders, and carbon fiber roof created a purposeful stance that visually communicated the departure from naturally aspirated elegance to forced-induction brutality.
editorial.motorsport_history: The F82 M4 dominated DTM racing and served as the basis for the track-focused GTS and CS variants. Its success in GT4 competition and various touring car championships validated the S55 engine's motorsport credibility despite initial skepticism from purists.
editorial.engine_character: The S55's twin-turbo inline-six delivers a relentless surge of torque from low RPMs, creating an addictive rush that builds to a satisfying crescendo. Unlike its naturally aspirated predecessor, this engine prioritizes crushing mid-range punch over high-rev theatrics.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 6-speed manual offers mechanical precision with a slightly heavy clutch, while the 7-speed DCT delivers lightning-fast shifts with customizable aggression levels. Both transmissions handle the S55's substantial torque output with confidence.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: The F82's chassis strikes an impressive balance between daily usability and track capability. Adaptive dampers allow seamless transitions from comfortable cruising to razor-sharp cornering, though the car always feels substantial and planted rather than lightweight and nimble.
editorial.steering_feel: Electric power steering provides excellent accuracy and reasonable feedback, though it lacks the organic connection of hydraulic systems. The steering weight builds naturally through corners, offering predictable and confidence-inspiring turn-in response.
editorial.brake_confidence: Massive Brembo brakes deliver exceptional stopping power with progressive pedal feel. The brake system handles repeated track sessions without fade while remaining perfectly manageable for street driving, epitomizing the M4's dual-purpose nature.
editorial.sound_signature: The S55 produces a distinctive growl with turbo whooshes and occasional pops on overrun. While different from the E92's naturally aspirated wail, the F82's soundtrack has its own character - more industrial and purposeful than melodious.
editorial.ideal_owner: Perfect for driving enthusiasts who want devastating performance with daily usability, appreciate modern turbo torque delivery, and value the prestige of M badge ownership combined with practical two-door coupe versatility.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Natural aspiration purists longing for high-rev engines, buyers seeking lightweight nimbleness over powerful muscle, or those prioritizing emotional connection over raw performance capability.
editorial.buyers_summary: Look for well-maintained examples with service records and avoid heavily modified cars. The S55 engine is robust but requires proper maintenance, and manual transmissions are increasingly rare and valuable.

expertReviews.title: BMW M4 Coupe Review (F82) | Is it a good M Car or is it just ...
pros: More approachable and manageable than expected
Excellent customization options with M1/M2 buttons
Classic BMW interior design that has aged well
Good fuel economy at 24-26 MPG for performance level
Harman Kardon sound system and heated seats
Stable feel when throttle is applied gradually
Fast acceleration - 0-100 km/h in 9 seconds
cons: Can be intimidating and aggressive with torque delivery
Risk of losing control if not respected
Low front splitter causes clearance concerns
Less visually appealing than M2
Requires time to properly configure settings

expertReviews.verdict: The F82 M4 is an exceptional car that's more approachable than initially feared. While it has intimidating power delivery that requires respect, proper throttle control makes it manageable and enjoyable. The reviewer appreciates its customization, interior quality, and reasonable fuel economy, but still prefers the M2 for its more compact size and pronounced styling. Good value option for those wanting M performance.

expertReviews.title: BMW M4 F82 buyers guide review (2014-2020) Avoid buying ...
pros: 50% of parts unique to M model with wider track width
Multiple performance variants available (425-500 HP)
Competition package offers good value for most buyers
Strong safety credentials from shared 3 series platform
cons: Common rear differential mount knocking issues
Expensive M4-specific suspension components when they fail
DCT gearbox mechatronic leak problems when cold
Carbon roof clear coat damage is very expensive to repair
Water ingress issues in boot/trunk area
Parasitic battery drain problems with expensive replacement costs
expertReviews.verdict: The BMW M4 F82 is a capable performance car with unique M-specific components and multiple variants from 425-500 HP. However, buyers should be aware of several common issues including rear differential problems, suspension component failures, DCT transmission issues, and expensive carbon roof repairs. Most issues affect 0.5-1% of production, but early detection and proper maintenance are crucial to avoid costly repairs.

expertReviews.title: BMW M4 Competition (F82) | Test Drive Review (#11)
pros: Last M4 Competition with manual transmission option
Excellent manual transmission that's easy to drive
Twin turbo inline-6 handles mountain terrain perfectly with no power loss
Lighter than predecessor E92 M3 by 160 pounds
Competition package offers great value for money
Strong stopping power with standard steel brakes
Rev matching works precisely and instantly
Excellent grip with Michelin Pilot Super Sport tires
cons: Electronic steering lacks communication compared to hydraulic steering
Active exhaust system instead of natural exhaust sound
Suspension is quite firm even in comfort mode

expertReviews.verdict: The F82 M4 Competition sits perfectly between the ultimate feel of the E92 M3 and the insane performance of the modern G82. As the last M4 Competition available with a manual transmission, it represents a sweet spot for enthusiasts who want modern turbo performance with traditional driving engagement. The twin-turbo inline-6 delivers strong performance especially at altitude, while the Competition package provides excellent value. Though it loses some steering feel compared to its predecessor, it remains a phenomenal driving experience.

expertReviews.verdict: The BMW M4 Competition is described as an 'absolute wolf in sheep's clothing' that delivers exceptional performance and handling. With 523hp and brutal acceleration (0-62 in 3.5 seconds), it excels on B-roads and corners with tenacity. The interior features gorgeous Silverstone leather design, though some plastic elements disappoint. Major drawbacks include muffled engine sound, thick steering wheel, and high option costs. Despite these issues, once seated, 'you will not want to move' as the car pivots around you.

Despite electronic additions that upset purists, it retains the raw, visceral feel of a proper M car. The reviewer emphasizes it's 'an awful lot of car for the money' starting around 20,000 used. The car handles both daily driving comfort and spirited driving exceptionally well.
